data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0) — redundant given count check below
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...)) — keep predicate check but improve message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active.");

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(expected, x.Count)` when you know the count |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser)` — item membership
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users)` — no nulls
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users)` — no duplicates

The `.All(predicate)` check has no built-in `CollectionAssert` equivalent, so `Assert.IsTrue` with a descriptive message is the right approach there.
